703. mea opera: thanks to me. — autument: men would say,- ie. si hoc facias. For autumo, cf. 324.

704. commissurum ut patiar fieri: unusual fullness of expres- sion, and therefore emphatic; ut potiar depends on commissurum (esse). —ne animum induxeris: don’t imaqine.

705. enim: indeed. This affirmative force, so common in Plautus, is preserved in the cornbinations sed enim, at enim. ete. — euge: bravo! (Greek εὖγε). — πάλαις encore! See notes on 187, 419.

706. hic uictust, eto: this reference to dramatic contests is undoubtedly taken from the Greek original.

707. ex argumento: literally, ‘⁴ in accord wit-h the plot,’⁷ ie. true to the port. The figure in the previous verse refers to rival dramatists : in this it refers to rival actors.

708. The original word following te is lost. See Appendix. This reference to the fining of actors probably comes from the Greek original, though we know nothing of the eustom referred to.
